and VIB, Flemish Institute for Biotechnology.

15
00:00:57.100 --> 00:00:58.780
And these are my disclosures.

16
00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:03.820
And in this session, I will kick off with an introduction on this topic

17
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:06.960
and give some background on our work on pks E. coli.

18
00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:11.580
And then we move on to two

19
00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:14.200
outstanding and distinguished

20
00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:19.320
scientists on this topic, Dr. Susan Bowman from University of Texas

21
00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:21.620
MD Anderson Cancer Center, and Dr.

22
00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:24.090
Wendy Garrett from Harvard Chan School of Public Health.

23
00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:29.420
So let me just start by introducing microbiota-host

24
00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:32.380
interactions in the colon under steady-state

25
00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:36.280
conditions. So as you can see on this image here, the

26
00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:39.280
human colon consists of around 10 million crypts

27
00:01:40.180 --> 00:01:42.700
spread across around two square meters.

28
00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:47.100
And you can see this organization with these invaginating crypts

29
00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:48.820
with stem cells at the bottom.

30
00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:53.720
And also the microbiota that are stained here by FISH probe in red.

31
00:01:54.260 --> 00:01:57.840
They are physically segregated from the intestinal epithelium by this inner mucus

32
00:01:57.920 --> 00:02:01.020
layer, which is around 50 microns in humans.

33
00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:05.020
And this architecture and spatial organization is very important for

34
00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:08.600
immune tolerance for normal tissue homeostasis.

35
00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.860
But it's also important that, of course, the stem cells are shielded from

36
00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:16.780
potential harmful substances in the gut lumen

37
00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:19.380
from dietary or microbial origin.

38
00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:20.820
And of course, there's

39
00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:25.400
strong communication between these different compartments, the

40
00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:29.410
microbiota, the intestinal epithelial cells, and underlying immune and

41
00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:32.300
stromal cells to maintain homeostasis.

42
00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:38.340
Now, it's important to mention that if there is genotoxic stress and

43
00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:42.360
mutations occurring in the differentiated enterocytes and

44
00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:46.380
other epithelial cells and surface-associated cells, this is usually

45
00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:50.260
harmless because, of course, the entire intestinal epithelium is renewed every few

46
00:02:50.300 --> 00:02:53.380
days, and these cells are anyhow shed and lost.

47
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.880
However, if mutations occur in the stem cells, they can

48
00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:01.609
be fixed within the clonal crypt, and upon accumulation of sufficient

49
00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:04.760
mutation, of course, this can lead to the development of

50
00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:06.200
colorectal cancer.

51
00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:11.030
Now on CRC epidemiology,

52
00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:15.660
colorectal cancer is the third most common and deadly type of cancer in most

53
00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:19.600
Western countries. And there's this alarming trend

54
00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:23.530
that in people under the age of 50, there's increased

55
00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:26.840
incidence of CRC development. And this is quite

56
00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:32.020
disturbing because these people usually present with more advanced disease.

57
00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:33.280
They're usually not picked up

58
00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:36.800
or not enrolled in these national screening

59
00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:38.880
platforms.

60
00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:43.820
And this increasing evidence over the past decades really shows that this

61
00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:47.609
is not a real genetic contribution, but mainly environmental and

62
00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:51.520
lifestyle factors that strongly impact on CRC development, such

63
00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:54.940
as unhealthy diets, so low in fiber, high in

64
00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.700
processed foods, high in saturated fats,

65
00:03:58.540 --> 00:04:02.500
a lot of red meat also. It's also associated to obesity

66
00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:06.270
and sedentary lifestyle, alcohol use, and antibiotics, and all these

67
00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:08.860
factors strongly impact on the intestinal

68
00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:12.460
microbiota. Now, there's increasing evidence that the

69
00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:16.300
microbiota actively contributes to colorectal cancer development

70
00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:20.200
through various mechanisms, and they can be broadly subclassified

71
00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:24.100
into four different mechanisms. The first mechanism

72
00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:27.600
is through direct genotoxicity. So some bacteria produce

73
00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:31.520
toxins that can directly induce mutations in the DNA, such as

74
00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:35.520
pks E. coli, for instance, that produce colibactin, which I will talk about

75
00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:39.420
later. The second mechanism is through metabolism of

76
00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:42.900
dietary components, and they can be beneficial metabolites from the

77
00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:45.120
fermentation of fibers,

78
00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:50.260
generating short-chain fatty acids or tryptophan degradation

79
00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:53.380
into indole derivatives that activate aryl hydrocarbon receptor.

80
00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:57.680
These are pathways that will stabilize the intestinal barrier

81
00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:01.560
and promote immune tolerance. On the other hand, diets rich

82
00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:04.420
in red meat and saturated fats,

83
00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:09.480
these will facilitate the production of harmful substances

84
00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:12.740
like hydrogen sulfate, secondary bile acids,

85
00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:17.100
N-nitroso compounds, nitrosamines, et cetera, that have a negative

86
00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:18.960
impact on this barrier, the mucus barrier,

87
00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:23.560
epithelial cell integrity, and will promote inflammation.

88
00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:28.680
So a disturbance of this intestinal barrier can also facilitate bacterial

89
00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:32.040
epithelial contact. This can also drive

90
00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:36.160
inflammatory signaling through pattern recognition receptor activation, which can

91
00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:40.140
promote the production of tumor-supportive cytokines such as IL-6,

92
00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:44.200
IL-23, TGF-beta, IL-10, and so forth, and can also

93
00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:48.160
stimulate the production of reactive oxygen and nitrogen species that can

94
00:05:48.180 --> 00:05:50.180
further contribute to genotoxicity.

95
00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:52.040
And then finally,

96
00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:56.340
microbes can also influence antitumor immunity through various

97
00:05:56.380 --> 00:06:00.020
mechanisms. So T-cell activation, exhaustion mechanisms,

98
00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:04.232
modulation of checkpoint modulationModulation of CAR

99
00:06:04.332 --> 00:06:07.892
T therapy response and so forth. So

100
00:06:08.332 --> 00:06:11.452
through complex metabolic interactions.

101
00:06:11.852 --> 00:06:15.812
And some of these mechanisms will be discussed in more detail during the session.

102
00:06:17.512 --> 00:06:17.872
So

103
00:06:18.832 --> 00:06:20.952
after my talk, we'll move on to

104
00:06:21.992 --> 00:06:23.472
our two distinguished speaker here, Dr.

105
00:06:23.602 --> 00:06:26.992
Susan Bowman, that will talk about intra-tumoral bacteria that reprogram

106
00:06:27.412 --> 00:06:31.202
tumor cell states and therapy response in colorectal cancer. And then Dr.

107
00:06:31.432 --> 00:06:35.392
Wendy Garrett at will talk about modulating the gut microbiome

108
00:06:35.432 --> 00:06:38.172
to enhance anti-tumor immunity in colorectal cancer.

109
00:06:39.692 --> 00:06:40.932
Now, I will start the session

110
00:06:41.812 --> 00:06:45.772
by talking about colibactin-driven genotoxicity and how this depends

111
00:06:45.932 --> 00:06:47.632
on epithelial adhesion.

112
00:06:49.652 --> 00:06:53.132
So colibactin is a toxin that is produced by

113
00:06:54.172 --> 00:06:56.572
several members of the Enterobacteriaceae family, like

114
00:06:57.392 --> 00:06:57.852
E. coli,

115
00:06:58.792 --> 00:07:02.392
and these pks+ E. coli harbor this pathogenicity island

116
00:07:02.972 --> 00:07:06.832
that contain 19 genes that together contain all

117
00:07:06.932 --> 00:07:10.812
enzymes required for generating this complex molecule here,

118
00:07:11.192 --> 00:07:11.872
colibactin.

119
00:07:13.252 --> 00:07:17.232
And this is a genotoxin. I will explain it a bit

120
00:07:17.712 --> 00:07:20.972
better in the next slides, but it's important to know that in healthy individuals,

121
00:07:21.052 --> 00:07:24.752
around 20% of people have pks E. coli in their

122
00:07:24.792 --> 00:07:28.742
intestine. However, the prevalence increases in

123
00:07:28.752 --> 00:07:32.232
people with intestinal inflammation, IBD, and even

124
00:07:32.292 --> 00:07:34.712
increases to 60% in people with CRC.

125
00:07:34.792 --> 00:07:38.112
So there's this clear tropism for the inflamed and

126
00:07:38.252 --> 00:07:42.192
neoplastic gut. Although it is present in a large number of

127
00:07:42.212 --> 00:07:44.092
people in healthy conditions.

128
00:07:45.752 --> 00:07:49.152
Now, there was this landmark paper a couple of years ago by the Cleaver's lab, and

129
00:07:49.212 --> 00:07:52.772
they show that if you inject intestinal organoids with these

130
00:07:52.932 --> 00:07:56.532
pks E. coli consecutively, so you inject them, then you treat them with

131
00:07:56.572 --> 00:08:00.512
antibiotics, you re-inject them over time for several weeks, and then you

132
00:08:00.652 --> 00:08:03.892
sequence the DNA of clonal expanded

133
00:08:04.332 --> 00:08:07.852
organoids. They found that there's a specific

134
00:08:07.972 --> 00:08:09.032
mutational signature

135
00:08:09.992 --> 00:08:13.591
linked to colibactin exposure in 80 rich DNA

136
00:08:13.632 --> 00:08:17.252
sequences. So they found that colibactin through

137
00:08:17.312 --> 00:08:21.072
this double cyclopropane warhead, can actually bind

138
00:08:21.112 --> 00:08:24.472
adenine residues on opposing DNA strands and thereby

139
00:08:24.532 --> 00:08:28.422
cross-link DNA, causing DNA damage responses that

140
00:08:28.452 --> 00:08:32.112
will induce typical colibactin-associated mutational signatures

141
00:08:32.612 --> 00:08:36.413
like the SBS88, so typical T to N mutations and the

142
00:08:36.533 --> 00:08:39.352
ID18 or T deletions.

143
00:08:40.372 --> 00:08:44.192
Now these mutational profiles are found in around one in eight

144
00:08:44.273 --> 00:08:48.252
colorectal tumors, and they're specifically enriched in patients with

145
00:08:48.372 --> 00:08:49.552
early onset CRC.

146
00:08:50.532 --> 00:08:54.392
And also this colibactin exposure and these mutations can cause

147
00:08:54.572 --> 00:08:58.492
mutations in typical tumor driver genes that have these 80 rich elements such

148
00:08:58.532 --> 00:08:59.332
as APC.

149
00:09:01.512 --> 00:09:05.292
Now, a recent paper by the Bascos lab nicely revealed

150
00:09:05.432 --> 00:09:06.472
the structure of

151
00:09:07.332 --> 00:09:10.452
active colibactin, which is a notoriously unstable molecule.

152
00:09:10.512 --> 00:09:14.072
However, whenever it cross-links DNA, it turns into a stable

153
00:09:14.972 --> 00:09:15.752
linked molecule.

154
00:09:16.652 --> 00:09:17.672
And they could show that

155
00:09:18.712 --> 00:09:22.282
this pseudosymmetrical structure here that you can see here

156
00:09:22.992 --> 00:09:25.312
with colibactin with this double cyclopropane

157
00:09:26.512 --> 00:09:29.992
electrophilic warheads can bind adenine residues

158
00:09:30.692 --> 00:09:34.092
on opposing DNA strands, and it has this

159
00:09:34.112 --> 00:09:38.052
concave structure where it nicely fits within the minor groove

160
00:09:38.172 --> 00:09:41.772
of the DNA and there can cross-link DNA in these 80 rich

161
00:09:41.912 --> 00:09:42.372
elements.

162
00:09:44.572 --> 00:09:45.532
Now, my lab

163
00:09:46.392 --> 00:09:50.232
mainly works with mouse models, and we study host microbe interactions

164
00:09:51.192 --> 00:09:53.692
using germ-free gnotobiotic mouse technology.

165
00:09:53.752 --> 00:09:54.532
So here you can see

166
00:09:55.412 --> 00:09:59.012
our facility where we can house mice in complete sterile conditions.

167
00:10:00.292 --> 00:10:04.192
But importantly, we have these regular black 6 experimental mice,

168
00:10:04.232 --> 00:10:07.512
but we can also rederive our transgenic models in germ-free

169
00:10:07.572 --> 00:10:11.452
conditions to actually verify whether a phenotype that develops

170
00:10:11.512 --> 00:10:15.392
in colonized condition also replicates in germ-free conditions.

171
00:10:16.292 --> 00:10:19.761
As you can see here through embryo transfer, so IVF generated embryos are

172
00:10:19.832 --> 00:10:22.252
transplanted in pseudopregnant foster mothers.

173
00:10:22.902 --> 00:10:26.492
And then we can also do targeted colonizations with bacteria of interest

174
00:10:26.912 --> 00:10:30.452
to see which bacteria can actually contribute to colorectal cancer development,

175
00:10:31.512 --> 00:10:35.292
and do specialized assays and do mouse colonoscopy,

176
00:10:35.692 --> 00:10:36.332
and so forth.

177
00:10:38.232 --> 00:10:39.712
Now, one of the mechanisms that we were

178
00:10:40.652 --> 00:10:42.352
very interested in a couple of years ago

179
00:10:43.352 --> 00:10:46.932
was this mechanism of EMT that is of course important in many

180
00:10:47.532 --> 00:10:51.032
epithelial tumors. So where the epithelial cells

181
00:10:51.072 --> 00:10:53.372
acquire more mesenchymal features.

182
00:10:54.512 --> 00:10:58.112
And this allows cells to acquire more invasive capacity, so

183
00:10:58.172 --> 00:11:02.152
it stimulates a tumor invasion and can also lead to metastasis later on.

184
00:11:02.972 --> 00:11:06.492
There's a number of transcription factors that are important here, like ZEB1, ZEB2,

185
00:11:06.672 --> 00:11:10.412
SNAI, SLUG. And we were interested in this ZEB2 transcription

186
00:11:10.512 --> 00:11:12.832
factor, as we found that in patients.

187
00:11:13.972 --> 00:11:17.062
So here you can see that in a normal colonic tissue,

188
00:11:17.592 --> 00:11:21.352
ZEB2 positive cells are only found here in mesenchymal cells in the lamina

189
00:11:21.362 --> 00:11:24.792
propria, but never in green epithelial cells.

190
00:11:24.872 --> 00:11:28.802
However, we found that in around 50% of CRC samples,

191
00:11:28.872 --> 00:11:32.492
we found also nuclear ZEB2 in intestinal

192
00:11:32.512 --> 00:11:35.152
epithelial cells. These are all ZEB2 positive tumors.

193
00:11:35.172 --> 00:11:38.932
This is a ZEB2 negative one. And others have also published the same.

194
00:11:39.012 --> 00:11:42.732
So indicating that ZEB2 expression, ectopic expression in epithelial cells

195
00:11:43.132 --> 00:11:46.292
is clinically relevant in a human setting.

196
00:11:47.052 --> 00:11:50.652
So therefore, we generated transgenic mice that

197
00:11:51.112 --> 00:11:54.832
expresses ZEB2 specifically in intestinal epithelial cells, and these

198
00:11:54.872 --> 00:11:58.772
mice develop spontaneous invasive colorectal cancer over time, which we

199
00:11:58.812 --> 00:12:01.172
can follow through mouse endoscopy.

200
00:12:01.912 --> 00:12:05.452
And if we make cross-sections through the colon

201
00:12:05.912 --> 00:12:09.412
and we fix the tissue and the mucus layer here, you can see that

202
00:12:09.492 --> 00:12:12.716
inAgain, in wild-type mice, you have this nice physical

203
00:12:12.756 --> 00:12:15.456
segregation in this inner mucus layer.

204
00:12:15.896 --> 00:12:19.675
However, in the Zap2 transgenic mice, we have a disturbance of this mucus

205
00:12:19.716 --> 00:12:23.636
layer. We have a barrier integrity loss and a facilitated bacterial

206
00:12:23.656 --> 00:12:25.816
epithelial contact and invasion.

207
00:12:26.636 --> 00:12:30.416
Now remarkably, germ-free Zap2 transgenic mice are completely protected,

208
00:12:31.496 --> 00:12:35.136
so showing that colorectal cancer development in this model is

209
00:12:35.156 --> 00:12:36.756
completely microbiota dependent.

210
00:12:37.416 --> 00:12:40.696
So this gave us an interesting mouse model

211
00:12:41.176 --> 00:12:44.636
to really study oncogenic specific oncobacteria in more

212
00:12:44.676 --> 00:12:48.376
detail. And one of our favorite bugs is this pks E. coli.

213
00:12:49.456 --> 00:12:53.116
So we compared the colonization of E.

214
00:12:53.156 --> 00:12:56.676
coli strains in our Zap2 transgenic mouse model in colonized mice.

215
00:12:57.296 --> 00:13:01.176
And we gavaged mice at six weeks of

216
00:13:01.256 --> 00:13:04.616
age for four weeks and then sacrificed them for analysis.

217
00:13:05.036 --> 00:13:08.896
So they were either colonized with 11G5, which is a CRC isolate,

218
00:13:09.056 --> 00:13:12.336
pks positive strain, but also E. coli Nissle

219
00:13:12.376 --> 00:13:14.696
1917 as a commensal control strain.

220
00:13:15.576 --> 00:13:18.856
And we found that after four weeks of colonization,

221
00:13:19.836 --> 00:13:23.196
only mice which were colonized with the 11G5 strain had severe

222
00:13:23.236 --> 00:13:26.876
exacerbation of a phenotype where you could see already strong tissue

223
00:13:26.916 --> 00:13:28.736
invasion in young mice,

224
00:13:29.756 --> 00:13:33.576
but not with mice which were colonized with this E. coli Nissle strain.

225
00:13:34.056 --> 00:13:37.796
So this work was really spearheaded by a talented postdoc in my lab,

226
00:13:37.896 --> 00:13:41.836
Maud Jans here. And if you quantify

227
00:13:41.876 --> 00:13:45.616
colon weight and his pathological scores, you can see that there's

228
00:13:45.716 --> 00:13:49.696
clearly increased disease only upon colonization with

229
00:13:49.896 --> 00:13:50.716
11G5.

230
00:13:52.356 --> 00:13:55.636
Now we wanted to verify whether this is colibactin-dependent, so we did the same

231
00:13:55.676 --> 00:13:59.256
experiment comparing 11G5 versus an

232
00:13:59.336 --> 00:14:03.116
isogenic mutant strain that lacks one of these essential genes for colibactin

233
00:14:03.176 --> 00:14:06.936
production, clbQ. So we see that only the

234
00:14:06.996 --> 00:14:10.956
wild-type 11G5 strain is capable of promoting the CRC development

235
00:14:10.996 --> 00:14:13.996
in this mouse model, not if the bacteria lack

236
00:14:14.416 --> 00:14:18.316
clbQ. So it's clear that also here increase

237
00:14:18.335 --> 00:14:22.285
in gamma-H2AX-positive cells only occurs in mice colonized

238
00:14:22.296 --> 00:14:26.016
with 11G5, not if they lack this essential gene clbQ for

239
00:14:26.116 --> 00:14:27.155
colibactin production.

240
00:14:28.796 --> 00:14:31.716
Now it's important to mention that actually Nissle, E.

241
00:14:31.756 --> 00:14:34.316
coli Nissle, is also a pks positive strain.

242
00:14:34.956 --> 00:14:38.416
So we were surprised that although both are pks positive, only

243
00:14:38.456 --> 00:14:42.436
11G5 promotes CRC development. So we wanted to figure out

244
00:14:42.496 --> 00:14:45.896
whether actually both produce decent amounts of colibactin.

245
00:14:46.336 --> 00:14:50.076
However, due to the unstable nature of colibactin, it's very hard to quantify

246
00:14:50.176 --> 00:14:53.856
through mass spectrometry. So we quantified

247
00:14:54.216 --> 00:14:58.016
NMA, which is a byproduct in the final maturation of pre-colibactin to

248
00:14:58.036 --> 00:15:01.396
colibactin, as a proxy for colibactin

249
00:15:01.696 --> 00:15:05.576
levels. And we found that although 11G5

250
00:15:05.616 --> 00:15:09.156
does produce more colibactin compared to Nissle, Nissle does

