503
00:29:01.276 --> 00:29:01.936
Good points. Yeah.

504
00:29:04.636 --> 00:29:08.306
Okay, thank you. So if there's no further questions, then we move on

505
00:29:08.896 --> 00:29:11.746
to the next speakers, and if I'm not mistaking, this will be Dr.

506
00:29:12.236 --> 00:29:14.216
Wendy Garrett from Harvard Med School.

507
00:29:22.616 --> 00:29:22.686
Thank you.

508
00:29:22.686 --> 00:29:26.556
Thank the organizers for inviting me, and Jens for the-- Lars for the

509
00:29:26.596 --> 00:29:27.236
introduction.

510
00:29:29.576 --> 00:29:30.566
Here are my disclosures.

511
00:29:32.226 --> 00:29:36.206
So we heard about sort of the negative sides of the microbiome, but it's not all

512
00:29:36.216 --> 00:29:39.506
bad. And so maybe this will spark a little bit of hope around

513
00:29:39.506 --> 00:29:42.976
metabolites that members of the microbiota make that promote

514
00:29:43.056 --> 00:29:44.086
anti-tumor immunity.

515
00:29:45.436 --> 00:29:47.316
So I'm going to tell you two stories.

516
00:29:47.376 --> 00:29:51.036
One's an accepted manuscript, just an excerpt from that, and then one story that's

517
00:29:51.076 --> 00:29:51.616
in revision.

518
00:29:53.176 --> 00:29:53.396
So

519
00:29:54.756 --> 00:29:58.396
we have a philosophy that we take, and it's approach that I hope I can

520
00:29:58.556 --> 00:30:02.516
maybe endorse that you all will take on, and that's how we can leverage

521
00:30:02.596 --> 00:30:06.276
available human microbiome data and mouse models to

522
00:30:06.336 --> 00:30:09.876
understand at the mechanistic level microbial

523
00:30:09.896 --> 00:30:13.475
contributions to colorectal cancer, whether they enhance

524
00:30:13.556 --> 00:30:17.536
susceptibility or resistance. And this project over the years has been

525
00:30:17.556 --> 00:30:21.336
led by three different postdoctoral fellows, all who have now moved on to

526
00:30:21.396 --> 00:30:25.116
independent positions. And the narrative flow will flip-flop a little bit

527
00:30:25.136 --> 00:30:27.416
between observations in humans and

528
00:30:27.456 --> 00:30:30.768
mice.So in 2018,

529
00:30:30.968 --> 00:30:34.788
three fabulous studies came out, and you probably are familiar

530
00:30:34.808 --> 00:30:38.268
with them if you are in this IO microbiome space.

531
00:30:38.928 --> 00:30:42.248
One was from MD Anderson, led by Jennifer Wargo.

532
00:30:42.428 --> 00:30:46.107
One was from University of Chicago, led by the Gajewski Lab.

533
00:30:46.128 --> 00:30:50.048
And a third came from France, Gustave Roussy, led by Laurence

534
00:30:50.058 --> 00:30:53.498
Zitvogel. And what they all found were different

535
00:30:53.498 --> 00:30:57.248
taxa, different microbes that patients harbored that

536
00:30:57.268 --> 00:31:00.508
distinguished individuals that went on to become

537
00:31:00.518 --> 00:31:04.018
non-responders or responders to anti-PD-1.

538
00:31:04.548 --> 00:31:07.988
But they all found something different, and that sort of created a

539
00:31:08.008 --> 00:31:11.218
psychic itch in my lab. And so we thought

540
00:31:11.288 --> 00:31:14.698
maybe we need to take a step back and not look at

541
00:31:14.748 --> 00:31:18.268
taxa, but look in these data sets and look at the metabolic

542
00:31:18.278 --> 00:31:21.448
pathways, because maybe that was a unifying feature that could

543
00:31:21.488 --> 00:31:25.388
explain what in the microbiome supported anti-tumor

544
00:31:25.448 --> 00:31:29.298
immunity. So time has passed over the last eight years,

545
00:31:29.348 --> 00:31:32.748
and now there are at least 17 IO studies,

546
00:31:33.148 --> 00:31:36.728
most using anti-PD-1. And so we looked at the most

547
00:31:36.808 --> 00:31:40.768
upregulated MetaSeq pathways, metabolic pathways

548
00:31:40.778 --> 00:31:43.868
enriched in responders versus non-responders.

549
00:31:44.448 --> 00:31:48.028
And we all see something different, maybe when we look at metabolic pathways.

550
00:31:48.088 --> 00:31:51.738
Maybe you see one carbon metabolism, maybe you just see methionine and

551
00:31:51.738 --> 00:31:52.138
cysteine.

552
00:31:52.978 --> 00:31:56.408
And so we're very curious in how we can

553
00:31:56.448 --> 00:31:59.988
promote anti-tumor immunity in colon cancer.

554
00:32:00.008 --> 00:32:03.948
And as many or most of you know, the vast majority of colon cancer

555
00:32:04.068 --> 00:32:07.268
is mismatch repair proficient, meaning that those

556
00:32:07.308 --> 00:32:11.028
individuals won't respond to the most IOs that are on the market.

557
00:32:11.478 --> 00:32:14.928
And so we looked at metabolic pathways in stool

558
00:32:15.428 --> 00:32:19.408
in normal, and normal means not colon cancer, not

559
00:32:19.448 --> 00:32:22.998
adenoma individuals, versus individuals with colon cancer.

560
00:32:23.448 --> 00:32:27.338
And we looked in that in conjunction with individuals that

561
00:32:27.368 --> 00:32:31.088
were responders versus non-responders to different IO

562
00:32:31.128 --> 00:32:34.328
therapeutics. So this is colon cancer.

563
00:32:34.398 --> 00:32:37.668
This is not colon cancer. So lung, renal,

564
00:32:37.708 --> 00:32:40.148
melanoma, hepatocellular carcinoma.

565
00:32:40.157 --> 00:32:43.878
And if you look at the pattern of this data, it's really remarkable that there's

566
00:32:43.948 --> 00:32:47.928
nothing in this quadrant. And so we've done a lot of analyses making sure that that

567
00:32:47.968 --> 00:32:51.808
holds up, taking out stage I, stage II, stage III, stage IV

568
00:32:51.948 --> 00:32:54.368
colon cancer and seeing if it changes the shape of the data.

569
00:32:54.828 --> 00:32:58.448
But again, what we saw was these pathways pop up again in

570
00:32:58.508 --> 00:33:02.428
individuals that lack colon cancer and individuals

571
00:33:02.448 --> 00:33:05.148
that were responsive to IO therapy.

572
00:33:06.608 --> 00:33:10.468
So there are a million ways you could take that data and run with

573
00:33:10.528 --> 00:33:13.038
it, and I'm just telling you what we did with it.

574
00:33:13.498 --> 00:33:17.068
And what we did is we talked to nutritional epidemiologists, and we

575
00:33:17.188 --> 00:33:20.958
asked how much methionine and cysteine do regular

576
00:33:20.988 --> 00:33:23.268
people in the United States consume.

577
00:33:23.637 --> 00:33:26.988
And we were interested in edge cases of normal.

578
00:33:27.488 --> 00:33:31.218
And that means people that are on the high end of normal consumption and

579
00:33:31.308 --> 00:33:33.858
people that are on the low end of normal consumption.

580
00:33:34.348 --> 00:33:37.928
And high for methionine and cysteine would not lead to

581
00:33:37.968 --> 00:33:41.768
hyperhomocysteinemia, and low is in

582
00:33:41.788 --> 00:33:45.228
no way, shape, or form methionine restriction, which is

583
00:33:45.348 --> 00:33:48.708
absolutely fascinating, but not at all what this study has to do with.

584
00:33:49.197 --> 00:33:53.048
And so we then created a diet in mice, which we then could

585
00:33:53.188 --> 00:33:56.768
recapitulate with subtle dietary changes in

586
00:33:56.828 --> 00:34:00.368
people or supplementation. And these are the

587
00:34:00.468 --> 00:34:04.268
amounts from baseline that these two diets differ in the

588
00:34:04.328 --> 00:34:08.169
mice. And the reason I put those values up there is if you look

589
00:34:08.208 --> 00:34:11.828
at papers and they supplement cysteine or methionine,

590
00:34:12.268 --> 00:34:16.069
it is usually 40 times the amount I'm showing you here,

591
00:34:16.609 --> 00:34:20.468
and it is usually 20 times less, usually, if you are a

592
00:34:20.548 --> 00:34:24.498
geek about diet. Okay. So these are the kinds of

593
00:34:24.528 --> 00:34:28.228
experiments that PIs love, because if there was any difference

594
00:34:28.248 --> 00:34:31.399
between the high or low diet, I would be excited.

595
00:34:31.548 --> 00:34:33.868
Sort of the winner-winner kinds of experiments in lab.

596
00:34:34.218 --> 00:34:37.968
And we started with a very simple model, a flawed

597
00:34:38.008 --> 00:34:41.468
model. As an oncologist, I can tell you I never see colon cancer in the

598
00:34:41.488 --> 00:34:44.248
flank. And if any of you have, please come up to me after.

599
00:34:44.649 --> 00:34:48.557
And the other problem with this model, or not problem, but just observation,

600
00:34:48.629 --> 00:34:51.788
is this is mismatch repair defective. It's MC38.

601
00:34:51.988 --> 00:34:54.488
But we saw a difference in the diet.

602
00:34:54.958 --> 00:34:57.568
The tumors were bigger in the low and smaller in the high.

603
00:34:58.388 --> 00:35:01.568
Now, are they really bigger? They are actually

604
00:35:01.908 --> 00:35:03.888
smaller with the high. And how do I know that?

605
00:35:03.908 --> 00:35:05.528
Because we compared it to the regular diet.

606
00:35:05.788 --> 00:35:09.778
And you might ask, do the mice not like the high diet, or do they eat

607
00:35:09.908 --> 00:35:12.968
less or whatever? No, they eat the same amount, and we measured their metabolic

608
00:35:13.028 --> 00:35:16.978
activity. Now, at the end of the day, you can see the tumors and

609
00:35:17.008 --> 00:35:19.238
the lovely pictures, and you can see the weights.

610
00:35:19.668 --> 00:35:23.348
But this is not very good for modeling what we wanted to model, so we

611
00:35:23.388 --> 00:35:26.758
switched to the Cdx2-Cre by floxed ApcMin mouse.

612
00:35:27.328 --> 00:35:29.268
These experiments are far longer.

613
00:35:29.308 --> 00:35:32.348
They make the postdocs far less happy and the students far less happy.

614
00:35:32.728 --> 00:35:36.268
But what we saw in the high diet is a lower number of

615
00:35:36.328 --> 00:35:40.128
adenocarcinoma events. And of course, there are more than

616
00:35:40.168 --> 00:35:42.368
one lesion in the mouse models, unlike people.

617
00:35:43.258 --> 00:35:46.738
The lesion diameter when we saw lesions were smaller, and the tumor weight was

618
00:35:46.768 --> 00:35:50.128
less. So that was interesting to us.

619
00:35:50.188 --> 00:35:54.028
And because we are microbiome scientists, we can't help ourselves but

620
00:35:54.048 --> 00:35:57.688
look in the microbiome. And what we saw was rather remarkable to us.

621
00:35:58.068 --> 00:36:02.028
We saw one taxa, and this is what we wanted to get away from, but one taxa that

622
00:36:02.068 --> 00:36:05.528
bloomed, and that taxon is called Musasprillum

623
00:36:05.688 --> 00:36:09.168
schatlerae. And what I'm showing you over here is that it

624
00:36:09.208 --> 00:36:12.328
really seems to have this interesting relationship with diet.

625
00:36:12.808 --> 00:36:16.198
It blooms in the high sulfur amino acid diet, whether you are a

626
00:36:16.228 --> 00:36:19.948
Cdx2-Cre by floxed ApcMin mouse, whether you are an

627
00:36:20.128 --> 00:36:23.928
SPF mouse that was unfortunate to receive MC38 in your flank,

628
00:36:24.448 --> 00:36:28.247
or if you are mice harboring the altered Schatla flora, which is a consortium

629
00:36:28.448 --> 00:36:31.108
of eight bugs, of which Musasprillum schatlerae is

630
00:36:31.248 --> 00:36:33.632
one.But what about people?

631
00:36:34.552 --> 00:36:38.392
So if there is a stool metagenome that is publicly available,

632
00:36:38.872 --> 00:36:42.852
I have looked at it and looked for Muscasprillum schadleri, and you're not going to

633
00:36:42.912 --> 00:36:44.572
find reliable reads in the stool.

634
00:36:45.392 --> 00:36:48.072
But where you will find reads is in the mucosa.

635
00:36:48.552 --> 00:36:52.142
So if you look at tissue-based studies where they have done

636
00:36:53.012 --> 00:36:56.912
profiling, you will find Muscasprillum schadleri in normal tissue,

637
00:36:56.972 --> 00:36:59.152
adenoma, but not in adenocarcinoma.

638
00:36:59.792 --> 00:37:03.652
So why? Well, like its name, Muscasprillum

639
00:37:03.792 --> 00:37:06.692
schadleri loves to live in the mucus.

640
00:37:07.132 --> 00:37:11.052
And here I'm showing you some fluorescence in situ hybridization, and the

641
00:37:11.112 --> 00:37:14.752
pink is the M. schadleri, and the green is

642
00:37:14.792 --> 00:37:18.632
mucin 2. Mucins in the mucus layer are

643
00:37:18.752 --> 00:37:22.192
very important, as we heard from the prior talk from Lars.

644
00:37:22.212 --> 00:37:23.672
And what we found was that

645
00:37:24.592 --> 00:37:27.952
the mucus layer is thicker, and there are more M.

646
00:37:28.112 --> 00:37:31.952
schadleri in response to the high sulfur amino acid diet

647
00:37:31.992 --> 00:37:35.892
versus the low. So why is that? So diet could

648
00:37:35.912 --> 00:37:39.372
affect the proliferation of goblet cells, and you could have more goblet

649
00:37:39.432 --> 00:37:42.172
cells and more mucus. That was not the case.

650
00:37:42.362 --> 00:37:46.032
But you did have more and thicker

651
00:37:46.352 --> 00:37:49.712
inner mucus layer. And this was truly driven

652
00:37:49.892 --> 00:37:53.692
by the diet and not by the microbiota, because, like

653
00:37:53.792 --> 00:37:57.372
Lars, we use a gnotobiotic facility where we can

654
00:37:57.432 --> 00:38:00.732
play with or toggle that variable of

655
00:38:01.692 --> 00:38:02.732
what microbes are there.

656
00:38:03.552 --> 00:38:04.292
So I'll tell you,

657
00:38:05.332 --> 00:38:09.172
we looked for many years to figure out what was the it factor of

658
00:38:09.252 --> 00:38:10.532
why the mucus was thicker.

659
00:38:11.432 --> 00:38:15.192
It's not stickier for M. schadleri. It's not because they're sulfur mucins.

660
00:38:15.212 --> 00:38:18.722
It's very simple. M. schadleri does not eat mucus,

661
00:38:19.172 --> 00:38:22.492
and many mucus-associated microbes do.

662
00:38:22.512 --> 00:38:25.812
So that's why it's thicker. So as any card-carrying

663
00:38:25.872 --> 00:38:29.772
immunologist will do when they're thinking about anti-tumor immunity, what do

664
00:38:29.812 --> 00:38:33.472
they look for? They look for the all-important CD8 positive T

665
00:38:33.932 --> 00:38:37.752
cell. And in this high diet, we saw more CD8

666
00:38:37.792 --> 00:38:41.192
positive T cells, and they made more gamma,

667
00:38:41.811 --> 00:38:45.512
not statistically significant. They made more granzyme B.

668
00:38:46.152 --> 00:38:48.452
They were less activated or exhausted.

669
00:38:49.512 --> 00:38:53.252
But that's not really interesting because we know those cells are important

670
00:38:53.372 --> 00:38:56.332
for human colon cancer and just about all human cancers.

671
00:38:56.792 --> 00:38:59.872
So what is upstream of the CD8 positive T cell?

672
00:39:00.272 --> 00:39:02.512
Can this diet and bug link get us there?

673
00:39:03.242 --> 00:39:06.512
And so what did we look at next? We looked at dendritic cells.

674
00:39:06.552 --> 00:39:10.152
And what was enriched in the tumor-draining lymph node was the

675
00:39:10.232 --> 00:39:13.932
CDC1 dendritic cell that cross-presents to the

676
00:39:13.992 --> 00:39:17.592
CD8 positive T cell, and diet increased that.

677
00:39:18.161 --> 00:39:20.772
And so now we wanted to shore up that link.

678
00:39:21.172 --> 00:39:24.792
And the way we shored up that link was using different

679
00:39:24.872 --> 00:39:26.832
mouse models. And so for the

680
00:39:27.972 --> 00:39:31.812
aficionados or people that love CDC1s, there are a couple ways to

681
00:39:31.852 --> 00:39:35.372
approach that. One is the Batf3

682
00:39:35.432 --> 00:39:39.372
knockout mouse, and we crossed that to the Cdx2-Cre by floxed

683
00:39:39.412 --> 00:39:43.272
Apc mouse, and we could toggle our low versus high sulfur amino

684
00:39:43.312 --> 00:39:45.252
acid diet and look for M. schadleri.

685
00:39:45.712 --> 00:39:49.192
And indeed, if you mess up the CDC1

686
00:39:49.272 --> 00:39:52.952
compartment, even if mucin is there, you lose the

687
00:39:53.012 --> 00:39:53.912
effect of diet.

688
00:39:55.092 --> 00:39:58.512
One tool is never enough. And so next we use the

689
00:39:58.592 --> 00:40:02.492
Zbt46 diphtheria toxin mice, made bone marrow

690
00:40:02.552 --> 00:40:06.472
chimeras, I can explain why if you're interested, with the Apc

691
00:40:06.532 --> 00:40:10.192
mice, and then deleted or treated those mice with

692
00:40:10.252 --> 00:40:14.232
diphtheria toxin. And so we removed the CDC1 compartment.

693
00:40:14.661 --> 00:40:18.392
And these experiments are labor-intensive and long, but they

694
00:40:18.452 --> 00:40:21.982
reassured us that there is something important or something going on with M.

695
00:40:22.112 --> 00:40:24.332
schadleri and CDC1 dendritic cells.

696
00:40:25.092 --> 00:40:29.012
So as anyone that knows and loves CDC1 dendritic cells, what do

697
00:40:29.052 --> 00:40:32.612
they have on their cell surface? They have XCR1 on their cell

698
00:40:32.692 --> 00:40:36.132
surface. And what that means is that they find

699
00:40:36.352 --> 00:40:39.912
XCL1, or lymphotactin, very chemoattractive.

700
00:40:40.032 --> 00:40:43.532
It's a wonderful stimulant for the CDC1.

701
00:40:43.542 --> 00:40:45.282
And I won't show you any single-cell data.

702
00:40:45.792 --> 00:40:48.912
It's in the manuscript that will be published at some point soon.

703
00:40:48.951 --> 00:40:52.472
But what we did is we neutralized the XCL1.

704
00:40:52.492 --> 00:40:56.312
And in so doing, we found that that was an important piece in

705
00:40:56.332 --> 00:40:59.992
this puzzle of M. schadleri, high sulfur amino acid diet,

706
00:41:00.452 --> 00:41:04.212
and CDC1s. And so as an immunologist, the next question you

707
00:41:04.372 --> 00:41:08.192
ask is who makes it? And if you read the textbooks, there is an

708
00:41:08.272 --> 00:41:10.932
answer, and the answer is NK cells.

709
00:41:11.252 --> 00:41:13.612
But the textbooks aren't always exactly right.

710
00:41:13.792 --> 00:41:17.132
And what we found in these studies from these mice

711
00:41:17.812 --> 00:41:21.712
was that the NKT cells were making that all-important

712
00:41:21.892 --> 00:41:22.512
XCL1.

713
00:41:23.652 --> 00:41:27.592
And not a lot of people think about NKT cells

714
00:41:27.952 --> 00:41:31.012
or innate T cells overall in anti-tumor immunity.

715
00:41:31.492 --> 00:41:34.272
There's some posters here that are getting on that, and I think we should

716
00:41:34.282 --> 00:41:37.412
definitely think more about innate T cell populations.

717
00:41:37.792 --> 00:41:41.151
And there is a wonderful reagent that Mitch Kronenberg

718
00:41:42.032 --> 00:41:45.852
from the San Diego area generated many years ago, and that is a

719
00:41:45.912 --> 00:41:49.692
neutralizing antibody. And what that antibody enabled us to

720
00:41:49.752 --> 00:41:53.432
do was to interrogate or pull apart this diet M.

721
00:41:53.572 --> 00:41:57.272
schadleri interaction. And what we found was that NKT

722
00:41:57.312 --> 00:42:00.372
cells are very, very important for this diet M.

723
00:42:00.452 --> 00:42:03.612
schadleri link. And so the next thing we did is begin to

724
00:42:03.792 --> 00:42:06.212
fractionate what M. schadleri is doing.

725
00:42:06.672 --> 00:42:10.552
And whether you are a mouse NKT cell or a human NKT

726
00:42:10.672 --> 00:42:14.352
cell, Muscasprillum schadleri and a conditioned

727
00:42:14.412 --> 00:42:17.562
media thereof, especially the organic fraction,

728
00:42:18.252 --> 00:42:20.912
stimulates the NKT cell to make more

729
00:42:21.152 --> 00:42:24.832
XCL1.Now, I wish I could show you the

730
00:42:24.852 --> 00:42:28.752
phospholipids today that Mucispirillum schadlerii

731
00:42:28.792 --> 00:42:32.672
is making. It is not just one. The microbial world is very

732
00:42:32.712 --> 00:42:35.752
complex. Mucispirillum schadlerii makes many.

733
00:42:36.432 --> 00:42:40.292
What I can tell you is those phospholipids do not

734
00:42:40.332 --> 00:42:44.052
bind the all-important antigen-presenting molecule for the

735
00:42:44.112 --> 00:42:47.952
NKT cell CD1d. So they stimulate the NKT

736
00:42:48.072 --> 00:42:51.992
cell independent of the molecule that stimulates its T

737
00:42:52.072 --> 00:42:52.772
cell receptor.

738
00:42:54.412 --> 00:42:57.952
So the microbiome and diet interactions are incredibly

739
00:42:57.992 --> 00:43:01.692
complex. You have to be in for the long haul if you're going to pull that apart.

740
