00:57:05.092 --> 00:57:08.762
There are lots of innate T cell populations, NK, NKT, gamma

977
00:57:08.802 --> 00:57:12.682
delta, MAIT, MR1-restricted T cells that are capable of

978
00:57:12.722 --> 00:57:13.842
killing tumor cells,

979
00:57:15.742 --> 00:57:19.682
period, end stop. And so we, I think, become so fixated maybe on

980
00:57:19.742 --> 00:57:23.422
CD8s and CD4 that I hope the field opens their eyes.

981
00:57:23.832 --> 00:57:27.342
And to open your eyes, only look at a single-cell RNA-seq data set of a primary

982
00:57:27.382 --> 00:57:31.242
tumor. Now, those cells can fluctuate in cell states, and they have

983
00:57:31.282 --> 00:57:34.381
to be making the right kinds of cytokines and

984
00:57:35.382 --> 00:57:39.062
hole-punching molecules to be effective anti-tumor

985
00:57:39.122 --> 00:57:40.862
immune cells. And

986
00:57:42.222 --> 00:57:45.302
you also asked me a question about MAIT cells, I think.

987
00:57:46.082 --> 00:57:48.642
Yeah. So the second question would be, I

988
00:57:49.842 --> 00:57:52.531
know that you also do lymphoma in colorectal cancer.

989
00:57:52.782 --> 00:57:54.072
We have not looked at

990
00:57:55.182 --> 00:57:58.702
cutaneous T cell lymphomas yet. We haven't looked at melanoma yet.

991
00:57:58.802 --> 00:58:02.372
We haven't looked at lung. We're very interested in

992
00:58:02.422 --> 00:58:06.382
endometrial cancer and urogenital cancers as well, but that's work in

993
00:58:06.422 --> 00:58:09.642
progress. And I wouldn't be surprised if they had a role.

994
00:58:13.162 --> 00:58:16.182
Okay, if there's no further questions, then we move on to the last speaker of this

995
00:58:16.222 --> 00:58:17.922
session, Dr. Susan Bowman.

996
00:58:24.482 --> 00:58:25.242
Thank you, Lars.

997
00:58:26.202 --> 00:58:28.982
Okay, I'm just waiting for my slides. Perfect.

998
00:58:29.182 --> 00:58:32.122
So good afternoon, everyone. It's a pleasure to be here with you today.

999
00:58:32.662 --> 00:58:34.262
And I'm going to shift gears slightly.

1000
00:58:34.322 --> 00:58:37.622
I'm going to talk about intratumoral microbes and how they can

1001
00:58:37.682 --> 00:58:41.202
modulate tumor cell states and impact therapy.

1002
00:58:42.342 --> 00:58:45.842
And since I began working in this field over a decade ago, we've really shifted our

1003
00:58:45.862 --> 00:58:49.682
focus from initially profiling whether or not there are actually even microbes

1004
00:58:50.002 --> 00:58:53.442
that are residing in tumors, to now trying to understand what they're

1005
00:58:53.502 --> 00:58:55.182
doing once they're within the tumors.

1006
00:58:55.212 --> 00:58:58.902
And today, I'm going to show you some of our work, along with work from across the

1007
00:58:58.942 --> 00:59:02.531
field, on understanding how these microbes modulate their

1008
00:59:02.562 --> 00:59:06.242
infected tumor niche and how that, in turn, will impact

1009
00:59:06.251 --> 00:59:07.822
patient treatment responses.

1010
00:59:08.982 --> 00:59:12.882
So as you all know, we've about 39 trillion microbes that are living

1011
00:59:12.962 --> 00:59:16.202
on and within our bodies, and most of this is within our

1012
00:59:16.222 --> 00:59:19.592
gastrointestinal tract. So in particular, our

1013
00:59:19.622 --> 00:59:23.561
colorectum, so about 95%. And it's here where these microbes, they

1014
00:59:23.582 --> 00:59:27.332
really set the stage for dynamic interactions in human health and

1015
00:59:27.382 --> 00:59:29.922
disease processes. That includes cancer.

1016
00:59:30.942 --> 00:59:34.782
And it really was enabled by the next generation

1017
00:59:34.842 --> 00:59:38.641
sequencing era and the availability of the human

1018
00:59:38.702 --> 00:59:42.382
reference genome that propelled this field forward, because

1019
00:59:42.482 --> 00:59:46.202
groups could begin to ask, what does the microbiome look like, or the

1020
00:59:46.262 --> 00:59:49.242
microbial profiles in human tissue?

1021
00:59:49.782 --> 00:59:53.522
How does that compare in cancer versus adjacent normal tissue?

1022
00:59:54.062 --> 00:59:57.522
And when groups began profiling this back in about 2010,

1023
00:59:57.722 --> 01:00:01.422
2011, they started observing that there were specific taxa

1024
01:00:01.462 --> 01:00:05.082
enriched within tumor tissue compared to adjacent normal tissue.

1025
01:00:05.102 --> 01:00:08.562
And surprisingly, many of these microbes were typically

1026
01:00:08.642 --> 01:00:12.592
oral microbes. They should've been just present in the mouth, but when tumors were

1027
01:00:12.902 --> 01:00:16.602
rising in the lower GI tract, these oral microbes were

1028
01:00:16.622 --> 01:00:20.242
infiltrating the tumor tissue, or at least associated with the

1029
01:00:20.302 --> 01:00:23.002
tissue based upon sequencing approaches.

1030
01:00:23.042 --> 01:00:24.742
So it raised a couple of questions.

1031
01:00:24.902 --> 01:00:28.722
How are these oral microbes, like Fusobacterium, actually getting to

1032
01:00:28.762 --> 01:00:32.042
colorectal tumors? And what were they doing once they

1033
01:00:32.382 --> 01:00:36.378
arrived at that tumor?And I think

1034
01:00:36.758 --> 01:00:40.498
big question after the initial discovery studies that

1035
01:00:40.578 --> 01:00:44.198
identified enrichment of particular microbes in colorectal tumors

1036
01:00:44.638 --> 01:00:47.978
was whether this spanned across patient populations.

1037
01:00:48.408 --> 01:00:51.448
And this led to more epidemiological studies,

1038
01:00:51.598 --> 01:00:55.488
population-based studies, and I would say this has been largely spearheaded

1039
01:00:55.498 --> 01:00:58.658
by Shuji Ogino at the Dana-Farber. Many of us have collaborated with him.

1040
01:00:59.158 --> 01:01:02.318
But he looked at data from the Nurses' Health Study, the Physician Follow-up Study,

1041
01:01:02.358 --> 01:01:06.278
so very large, prospective patient cohorts where

1042
01:01:06.318 --> 01:01:10.278
individuals were followed over time prior to the development of cancer.

1043
01:01:10.318 --> 01:01:14.268
They looked at diet. They looked at behavioral aspects.

1044
01:01:14.278 --> 01:01:17.578
And then in those individuals that did develop tumors, he

1045
01:01:17.618 --> 01:01:21.518
profiled the amount of Fusobacterium through qPCR, so

1046
01:01:21.578 --> 01:01:25.418
comparing tumors that had relatively high, intermediate,

1047
01:01:25.568 --> 01:01:29.458
or low levels of Fusobacterium. And what these studies saw

1048
01:01:29.558 --> 01:01:33.038
was a correlation between the amount of this

1049
01:01:33.078 --> 01:01:36.498
microbe in the tumor and patient clinical and

1050
01:01:36.538 --> 01:01:40.198
molecular data. So enrichment of Fusobacterium in

1051
01:01:40.237 --> 01:01:44.218
right-sided colon cancer is associated with certain types of mutations like

1052
01:01:44.238 --> 01:01:47.718
BRAF V600E, MSI high tumors.

1053
01:01:48.238 --> 01:01:52.198
But also in patients that had a Western diet,

1054
01:01:52.298 --> 01:01:56.078
they were more likely to have Fusobacterium-positive colorectal

1055
01:01:56.118 --> 01:01:59.818
tumors. And why this mattered was because patients that had

1056
01:02:00.098 --> 01:02:03.638
high levels of Fusobacterium in their tumor, they had poorer overall

1057
01:02:03.698 --> 01:02:07.458
survival. And we're still trying to figure out why exactly that

1058
01:02:07.538 --> 01:02:11.458
is. But the importance here was that it showed us this wasn't just a

1059
01:02:11.538 --> 01:02:13.758
random association, that it was linked.

1060
01:02:13.798 --> 01:02:17.458
Its presence was linked with biology of colorectal

1061
01:02:17.518 --> 01:02:21.508
cancer. And that pushed us to really ask what's happening in

1062
01:02:21.538 --> 01:02:24.578
these patient tumors when this microbe is present.

1063
01:02:25.618 --> 01:02:29.578
But before I jump in and start talking about Fusobacterium in more detail,

1064
01:02:29.678 --> 01:02:33.318
I did want to highlight many studies, very important functional

1065
01:02:33.398 --> 01:02:37.158
studies over the last several years that have demonstrated a role for

1066
01:02:37.578 --> 01:02:41.458
microbes in cancer initiation, progression, and treatment response.

1067
01:02:41.498 --> 01:02:43.977
And this by no means is a comprehensive list.

1068
01:02:44.618 --> 01:02:48.238
But as we just heard from Lars, we heard about this pks positive E.

1069
01:02:48.258 --> 01:02:51.718
coli and colibactin directly inducing mutational signatures.

1070
01:02:52.318 --> 01:02:55.998
And I do want to give a shout-out to Christian Jobin, who I would say is really the

1071
01:02:56.047 --> 01:03:00.018
godfather of pks positive E. coli and linking it to colorectal cancer and really

1072
01:03:00.418 --> 01:03:04.118
bringing it to our attention. But in addition to the pks

1073
01:03:04.198 --> 01:03:08.168
positive E. coli, there are many other taxa that are now emerging as

1074
01:03:08.238 --> 01:03:12.218
having genotoxic roles in helping initiate

1075
01:03:12.498 --> 01:03:16.398
colorectal cancer. This includes recent work from

1076
01:03:16.598 --> 01:03:20.418
Noah Palm's group, where they looked at Morganella morganii, as

1077
01:03:20.458 --> 01:03:22.898
we've just heard from Lars, who described this work.

1078
01:03:23.438 --> 01:03:27.258
We've also seen recent work come out from Cindy Sears and Julia Drew, who's looking

1079
01:03:27.278 --> 01:03:31.138
at Citophyl and this microbe that is present in

1080
01:03:31.158 --> 01:03:34.668
colorectal tumors but also present in the mucosal slurries from

1081
01:03:34.838 --> 01:03:38.748
tumors from patients with colorectal cancer and showed in mouse models that this

1082
01:03:38.758 --> 01:03:42.678
could increase tumor genesis. And again, work from Christian

1083
01:03:42.698 --> 01:03:46.478
Jobin's group that is looking at Campylobacter jejuni, this

1084
01:03:46.538 --> 01:03:49.818
microbe is an organism that's associated with food poisoning.

1085
01:03:49.858 --> 01:03:53.148
It is a pathogen in the gut, and it has a cytolysin V descending

1086
01:03:53.238 --> 01:03:56.498
toxin that has been shown through this work to induce or

1087
01:03:56.558 --> 01:03:59.938
increase the number of tumors in mouse models.

1088
01:03:59.978 --> 01:04:03.938
And more recently, work that was published, a beautiful study in cell

1089
01:04:03.978 --> 01:04:07.578
host microbe demonstrating the role of Campylobacter in colorectal

1090
01:04:07.618 --> 01:04:08.928
cancer metastases.

1091
01:04:10.558 --> 01:04:13.858
And in addition, as we've just talked about as well, these microbes are never in

1092
01:04:13.938 --> 01:04:16.478
isolation. It's never just a single microbe present in the tumor.

1093
01:04:16.528 --> 01:04:20.058
They occur in communities. And Cindy Sears, a while back, looked at

1094
01:04:20.078 --> 01:04:22.258
synergistic effects between pks positive E.

1095
01:04:22.278 --> 01:04:26.178
coli and enterotoxigenic Bacteroides fragilis in patients with

1096
01:04:26.218 --> 01:04:30.118
familiar adenomatous polyposis, demonstrating that they work together to

1097
01:04:30.158 --> 01:04:33.858
enhance mutations within the colonic

1098
01:04:33.918 --> 01:04:36.558
epithelial cells. So they had a synergistic effect.

1099
01:04:37.428 --> 01:04:41.398
There's been studies demonstrating the indirect ability of microbes to contribute

1100
01:04:41.418 --> 01:04:44.898
to chemoresistance by changing cell states, for example,

1101
01:04:45.038 --> 01:04:48.158
inducing autophagy that led to resistance to

1102
01:04:48.178 --> 01:04:51.898
chemotherapeutics and also directly contributing to

1103
01:04:51.918 --> 01:04:55.018
chemotherapy. So work from my group have demonstrated that

1104
01:04:55.458 --> 01:04:59.278
50% of the patients we assessed with colorectal cancer harbored

1105
01:04:59.318 --> 01:05:03.158
bacteria that could metabolize 5-fluorouracil into an

1106
01:05:03.438 --> 01:05:06.908
inactive form. And that work was also assessed

1107
01:05:07.038 --> 01:05:07.758
by

1108
01:05:08.598 --> 01:05:12.458
Peter Turnbaugh's group that really shed light on the preTA operon and the presence

1109
01:05:12.498 --> 01:05:16.078
of this preTA operon in our gut microbes, metabolizing routine

1110
01:05:16.178 --> 01:05:19.718
chemotherapeutic drugs into an inactive form.

1111
01:05:19.748 --> 01:05:23.608
And then prior work from my work as a postdoc, we demonstrated

1112
01:05:23.618 --> 01:05:26.578
that these microbes are not just present in the primary colorectal tumors, but they

1113
01:05:26.618 --> 01:05:30.148
persist with the cancer as it spreads in distance like disease and

1114
01:05:30.178 --> 01:05:33.798
metastases. And when we looked at the microbial communities in the

1115
01:05:34.038 --> 01:05:37.858
metastatic colorectal cancer, they resembled more the primary tumor than

1116
01:05:37.878 --> 01:05:41.538
liver metastases, so demonstrating that these microbes are an intrinsic

1117
01:05:41.578 --> 01:05:44.398
component of the tumor microenvironment.

1118
01:05:45.478 --> 01:05:49.078
And when we think about the tumor microenvironment, we'll often think about the

1119
01:05:49.118 --> 01:05:52.498
cancer cell itself. What are the mutations that are present?

1120
01:05:52.538 --> 01:05:55.438
Are they driving the cancer? Can we target them for treatment?

1121
01:05:56.038 --> 01:05:59.878
But we know that within these patient tumors, these cancer epithelial

1122
01:05:59.898 --> 01:06:02.748
cells are surrounded by a network of nonmalignant cells.

1123
01:06:02.758 --> 01:06:05.958
We've got infiltrating immune cells that we've just heard about, and they can have

1124
01:06:05.978 --> 01:06:09.778
pro or antitumorigenic effects. We've endothelial cells. We've fibroblasts.

1125
01:06:10.238 --> 01:06:12.858
And now, at least in colorectal cancers, we have this

1126
01:06:12.998 --> 01:06:16.278
tumor-infiltrating microbial component.

1127
01:06:16.358 --> 01:06:20.268
So an area that my group is particularly interested in is understanding what

1128
01:06:20.298 --> 01:06:22.938
happens when these microbes enter the tumor.

1129
01:06:23.598 --> 01:06:26.888
Where are they localized? What are the human cells they're interacting with?

1130
01:06:27.278 --> 01:06:30.638
And importantly, what are the consequences of these host

1131
01:06:30.798 --> 01:06:34.678
microbial interactions?And here I'm showing you

1132
01:06:34.778 --> 01:06:38.418
a video of a patient's colon adenocarcinoma tumor.

1133
01:06:38.427 --> 01:06:42.118
And we've carried out RNA scope on this tumor where Fusobacterium is

1134
01:06:42.198 --> 01:06:45.078
red, and we have Eubacteria as a cyan color.

1135
01:06:45.618 --> 01:06:48.438
So as we're looking around this tissue, you can see that these microbes are not

1136
01:06:48.478 --> 01:06:50.218
just present on the surface of the tumor.

1137
01:06:50.258 --> 01:06:53.278
They have infiltrated, invaded the tumor tissue.

1138
01:06:54.148 --> 01:06:58.078
But they're very focally localized. They're not distributed everywhere.

1139
01:06:58.138 --> 01:07:01.298
So this tells us that once the microbes have infiltrated the

1140
01:07:01.338 --> 01:07:05.318
tissue, they are not universally present across the tumor tissue, but they

1141
01:07:05.338 --> 01:07:09.158
have a heterogeneous distribution. So that's interesting.

1142
01:07:09.358 --> 01:07:13.338
What allows the microbes to invade, survive, persist in one

1143
01:07:13.398 --> 01:07:17.198
region of the tumor, but completely are absent from another region of the

1144
01:07:17.258 --> 01:07:18.458
same patient's tumor?

1145
01:07:20.218 --> 01:07:23.958
And to understand this, we applied a range of approaches, and we were

1146
01:07:23.967 --> 01:07:26.178
taking hold of the spatial biology era.

1147
01:07:26.778 --> 01:07:29.918
And even these technologies that I'm showing you right now are pretty much

1148
01:07:29.958 --> 01:07:33.198
outdated, but this was 10x Visium spatial transcriptomics.

1149
01:07:33.778 --> 01:07:37.458
And we use computational subtraction approaches that I had mentioned

1150
01:07:37.498 --> 01:07:41.298
earlier that had actually led to the discovery of microbes in

1151
01:07:41.518 --> 01:07:45.178
tumor tissue. But here, when we applied this approach, we

1152
01:07:45.198 --> 01:07:49.058
wanted to assess what are the microbial taxa within the

1153
01:07:49.098 --> 01:07:52.558
tumor tissue, could we map them in situ directly in the

1154
01:07:52.598 --> 01:07:53.168
patient's

1155
01:07:54.198 --> 01:07:56.638
tumor tissue without losing that spatial biology.

1156
01:07:57.098 --> 01:08:00.718
And this was an adaption of 10x Visium spatial transcriptomics, and I would say

1157
01:08:00.758 --> 01:08:04.478
it's very important to always include an orthogonal approach whenever you're

1158
01:08:04.538 --> 01:08:07.258
assessing something, especially with sequencing technologies.

1159
01:08:07.718 --> 01:08:11.638
So we would always carry out RNA scope on a sequential section, and

1160
01:08:11.678 --> 01:08:14.268
as a sanity check, ask, does this match up?

1161
01:08:14.308 --> 01:08:18.178
Is what we're seeing make sense? So here you can see RNA scope on the

1162
01:08:18.239 --> 01:08:21.918
left. It was a sequential section to our 10x Visium spatial

1163
01:08:21.938 --> 01:08:25.858
transcriptomics, where we could map our microbial reads directly back

1164
01:08:25.898 --> 01:08:29.838
to these capture spots based upon our spatial barcode, which

1165
01:08:29.898 --> 01:08:33.608
acts like an area code. And as you know, this UMI is a proxy for

1166
01:08:33.678 --> 01:08:37.558
transcriptional load. So it gave us an indication of the different taxa that

1167
01:08:37.579 --> 01:08:39.159
were localized to the tumor tissue.

1168
01:08:39.218 --> 01:08:42.718
We saw they mostly co-occurred together in very specific regions.

1169
01:08:43.358 --> 01:08:47.239
What we typically see is that they infiltrate from the luminal region of the

1170
01:08:47.279 --> 01:08:51.079
tissue into the tumor, and that's where the highest density is

1171
01:08:51.138 --> 01:08:54.558
localized. But in addition to Fusobacterium, we saw Bacteroides,

1172
01:08:54.619 --> 01:08:56.838
Leptotrichia, Gemella, Compylobacter.

1173
01:08:57.258 --> 01:09:00.958
Often, our Compylobacter is concisus and ureticicus.

1174
01:09:01.638 --> 01:09:05.079
But this really confirms that these microbes have a heterogeneous distribution

1175
01:09:05.098 --> 01:09:07.818
within tumor tissue, and it's not just a single taxa.

1176
01:09:07.858 --> 01:09:11.779
They're communities that are infiltrating the tissue and coexisting

1177
01:09:11.818 --> 01:09:15.409
together. But what are they doing once they get into the tissue?

1178
01:09:15.438 --> 01:09:18.398
And that's, again, the key questions we're trying to figure out.

1179
01:09:18.958 --> 01:09:22.848
And to get some insight into this, we applied another spatial profiling approach.

1180
01:09:22.909 --> 01:09:26.518
This time we used Geomix. And we looked at

1181
01:09:26.527 --> 01:09:30.428
antibodies. We looked at a 77-panel antibody, and I think now there's over

1182
01:09:30.518 --> 01:09:33.838
1,000 different antibodies you can look at, so the technology has just soared

1183
01:09:33.898 --> 01:09:37.699
ahead. But when we applied this approach, we again carried out RNA

1184
01:09:37.739 --> 01:09:41.598
scope, and we assessed regions that were positive for bacteria

1185
01:09:41.619 --> 01:09:43.798
versus regions that were negative for bacteria.

1186
01:09:44.628 --> 01:09:47.998
And we looked at immune cell functions and also epithelial cell functions.

1187
01:09:48.579 --> 01:09:52.498
And what we saw was that these microbes, they were localized to immunosuppressive

1188
01:09:52.558 --> 01:09:56.318
regions. So these were regions that were characterized by myeloid cell

1189
01:09:56.358 --> 01:09:59.718
infiltration. We saw arginase 1, we saw CD66B.

1190
01:10:00.418 --> 01:10:04.098
We saw a reduction in T cells, so less CD4, CD8, CD3 T

1191
01:10:04.138 --> 01:10:07.798
cells, but we saw an increase in checkpoints, so

1192
01:10:07.898 --> 01:10:11.438
CTLA4, PD1, LAG3, VISTA. And we also saw an

1193
01:10:11.498 --> 01:10:14.558
upregulation of MAP kinases such as Fosl APK,

1194
01:10:14.638 --> 01:10:17.978
Phospho-p38. So they had very distinct

1195
01:10:18.098 --> 01:10:21.678
functional features, the regions that were colonized by these microbes.

1196
01:10:21.698 --> 01:10:22.638
This makes sense.

1197
01:10:23.918 --> 01:10:25.998
But this was all correlative at a period of time.

1198
01:10:26.027 --> 01:10:29.858
It didn't tell us whether or not these microbes were actively modulating their

1199
01:10:29.898 --> 01:10:33.418
infected tumor niche or whether they were colonizing a

1200
01:10:33.438 --> 01:10:37.198
preexisting environment. So in order to figure this out, we

1201
01:10:37.258 --> 01:10:41.178
always have to go back to the lab. We usually start with the patient, and then

1202
01:10:41.218 --> 01:10:44.058
we try to model what we're seeing in the patient back in the lab.

1203
01:10:44.078 --> 01:10:47.978
And here I'm showing you co-culture experiments with a clinical isolate

1204
01:10:48.118 --> 01:10:52.097
of Fusobacterium nucleatum. And I'm using the sensu

1205
01:10:52.178 --> 01:10:52.597
latu

1206
01:10:53.838 --> 01:10:57.418
for Fusobacterium nucleatum, just out of ease, but this is a subspecies animalis

1207
01:10:57.818 --> 01:11:00.638
that we had cultured from a patient's colorectal tumor.

1208
01:11:01.598 --> 01:11:05.528
So on the left, you can see cancer cell spheroids co-cultured with neutrophils that

1209
01:11:05.558 --> 01:11:09.078
are pink without Fusobacterium. And on the right, we have added our clinical

1210
01:11:09.158 --> 01:11:13.058
isolate of Fusobacterium. And what you can appreciate is that in the presence of

1211
01:11:13.068 --> 01:11:16.798
Fusobacterium, these neutrophils migrate into the center of the spheroid.

1212
01:11:17.218 --> 01:11:20.358
They form these large aggregates, and they become trapped.

1213
01:11:20.838 --> 01:11:24.558
So resembling this myeloid cell recruitment that we see in the patient tumor

1214
01:11:24.618 --> 01:11:26.198
tissue, and this is not surprising.

1215
01:11:26.258 --> 01:11:29.018
The cancer epithelial cells, they're producing

1216
01:11:29.058 --> 01:11:32.918
CXCL8. They're just screaming out for neutrophils to come

1217
01:11:32.978 --> 01:11:36.857
in and to attack the bacteria or remove the bacteria.

1218
01:11:38.438 --> 01:11:40.278
And what about the epithelial cells?

1219
01:11:40.318 --> 01:11:43.258
So here I'm going to show you cancer cell spheroids in green.

1220
01:11:43.778 --> 01:11:47.058
On the left, no bacteria, and on the right, we've added again our clinical

1221
01:11:47.138 --> 01:11:50.178
isolate of Fusobacterium nucleatum, which is seen in pink.

1222
01:11:50.958 --> 01:11:54.218
So without bacteria, we see the cancer epithelial cells. They grow en masse.

1223
01:11:54.238 --> 01:11:58.038
The entire spheroid enlarges. But when Fusobacterium is present, we

1224
01:11:58.138 --> 01:12:01.828
see migration occurring at the single-cell level, and it's

1225
01:12:01.838 --> 01:12:05.658
bringing Fusobacterium with it. And we also saw upregulation of

1226
01:12:05.718 --> 01:12:09.308
MAP kinases in a dose-dependent manner in the presence of

1227
01:12:09.358 --> 01:12:13.198
Fusobacterium. And additionally, we've carried out single-cell sequencing here,

1228
01:12:13.298 --> 01:12:17.288
so we can see alterations in epithelial, mesenchymal transition,

1229
01:12:17.778 --> 01:12:19.938
and extracellular matrix remodeling.

1230
01:12:22.018 --> 01:12:24.138
But single-cell sequencing,

1231
01:12:25.058 --> 01:12:28.918
it was very beneficial for our initial study, and we developed a

1232
01:12:28.958 --> 01:12:32.908
tool called InvadeSeq, but the challenge there was you lose spatial biology.

1233
01:12:32.918 --> 01:12:35.858
And as I mentioned, tools have moved forward dramatically.

1234
01:12:36.018 --> 01:12:39.418
So now we have the ability to look at single cells and even

1235
01:12:39.478 --> 01:12:43.118
subcellular-level resolution spatially, directly within patient

1236
01:12:43.178 --> 01:12:47.148
specimens. So the next part of the talk is the question that

1237
01:12:47.158 --> 01:12:50.478
we had is whether these microbes functionally impacted the tumor

1238
01:12:50.538 --> 01:12:54.298
microenvironment at the single cellspatial level.

1239
01:12:54.738 --> 01:12:57.718
So as you can see here on the left, we can see Fusobacterium.

1240
01:12:58.248 --> 01:13:01.908
Not all of the Fusobacterium is directly within the tumor

1241
01:13:02.028 --> 01:13:04.398
cells, in the cells in the tumor microenvironment.

1242
01:13:04.828 --> 01:13:07.718
On the right, you can see confocal microscopy of a co-culture, and this is the

1243
01:13:07.728 --> 01:13:10.538
center of a Z stock. So yes, indeed, there are cells that are

1244
01:13:10.568 --> 01:13:14.188
intracellular, but also there is bacteria on the outside of the

1245
01:13:14.208 --> 01:13:18.128
cells. So we really wanted to assess spatially the difference

1246
01:13:18.168 --> 01:13:22.128
between extracellular bacteria, intracellular bacteria, and how does

1247
01:13:22.268 --> 01:13:25.708
load matter when we start thinking about remodeling the tumor

1248
01:13:25.768 --> 01:13:28.948
microenvironment. And this was work that was led by Jorge Nino,

1249
01:13:29.708 --> 01:13:32.108
Falk Ponnett, and Javier Gomez in my group.

1250
01:13:33.208 --> 01:13:37.168
So we can apply spatial biology tools, AI tools such as Visium,

1251
01:13:37.568 --> 01:13:41.528
where we can now quantify the bacterial signals externally outside

1252
01:13:41.568 --> 01:13:43.428
of the cell and the cell associated.

1253
01:13:43.898 --> 01:13:47.768
And when we applied this to patient specimens, what we could

1254
01:13:47.828 --> 01:13:51.648
measure was the microbial counts outside of the cell

1255
01:13:51.728 --> 01:13:53.848
versus the total multiplicity of infection.

1256
01:13:54.408 --> 01:13:58.208
And what we observed is that most of the bacterial signals in

1257
01:13:58.268 --> 01:14:00.328
these colorectal tumors are actually extracellular.

1258
01:14:00.468 --> 01:14:03.948
So it's extracellular bacteria within the tumor microenvironment.

1259
01:14:07.008 --> 01:14:10.868
We applied this to a range of patient cohorts, including oral cancers or

1260
01:14:11.068 --> 01:14:14.808
colorectal cancer patient cohorts, and even a mouse model for colorectal cancer,

1261
01:14:14.888 --> 01:14:18.368
where you can see Fusobacterium as red and new bacteria in cyan.

1262
01:14:19.528 --> 01:14:23.238
And what we see is that as bacterial load increases,

1263
01:14:24.468 --> 01:14:28.428
we have an increased distance between the human

1264
01:14:28.528 --> 01:14:30.488
cells within that tumor microenvironment.

1265
01:14:31.228 --> 01:14:34.788
So these microbes are disrupting cellular

1266
01:14:34.808 --> 01:14:38.798
interactions within the tumor microenvironment based upon their physical

1267
01:14:38.828 --> 01:14:42.188
entity, and this is something I'll show again in a moment.

1268
01:14:42.208 --> 01:14:46.088
So we can measure the distances between the cells, and we can also measure the

1269
01:14:46.108 --> 01:14:49.408
densities in the regions where these microbes are localized.

1270
01:14:52.588 --> 01:14:56.448
This disruption of cell-to-cell interactions, it has a consequence, and here

1271
01:14:56.488 --> 01:14:59.458
I'm showing you a protein analysis through immunohistochemistry.

1272
01:14:59.948 --> 01:15:03.928
What we see in these regions with the highest density of bacteria is actually a

1273
01:15:03.968 --> 01:15:07.468
reduction in Ki-67, so lower levels of proliferation.

1274
01:15:08.028 --> 01:15:11.628
And when we saw this, initially, we were really surprised because most of the

1275
01:15:11.668 --> 01:15:15.528
literature centering on Fusobacterium will tell you that it induces

1276
01:15:15.568 --> 01:15:18.168
hyperproliferation of cancer epithelial cells.

1277
01:15:18.628 --> 01:15:21.708
But we did not see that, and we did not see that in our patients.

1278
01:15:21.788 --> 01:15:24.968
And we went back to the lab to assess that further.

1279
01:15:25.208 --> 01:15:26.488
And here you can see

1280
01:15:27.948 --> 01:15:31.788
cells that were with LifeAct, we have no bacteria on the

1281
01:15:31.828 --> 01:15:35.648
left, and we have Fusobacterium exposed on the right.

1282
01:15:36.408 --> 01:15:40.148
And what you can monitor over time is proliferation, and you can

1283
01:15:40.208 --> 01:15:42.167
monitor cell-to-cell interactions.

1284
01:15:42.248 --> 01:15:42.408
So

1285
01:15:43.368 --> 01:15:47.108
with high density exposure to Fusobacterium, we do not

1286
01:15:47.168 --> 01:15:49.948
see an increase in cancer epithelial cell proliferation.

1287
01:15:50.408 --> 01:15:53.828
We see disruption of epithelial cell interactions.

1288
01:15:54.558 --> 01:15:58.128
The cells remain viable. We've assessed this through propidium iodide, but they are

1289
01:15:58.168 --> 01:16:02.028
not entering a hyperproliferation state as the field previously thought.

1290
01:16:03.928 --> 01:16:07.508
We wanted to gain more information on this, and we used a FOUGE construct to assess

1291
01:16:07.648 --> 01:16:11.348
cell cycle. So we can assess cells that are in different stages of cell cycle,

1292
01:16:11.648 --> 01:16:15.468
G0, G1, S, G2, and M. And on the

1293
01:16:15.548 --> 01:16:19.528
left, you will see zero multiplicity of infection. So this is our control.

1294
01:16:19.568 --> 01:16:23.548
And then we have an MOI of one, 10, and 100 Fusobacterium

1295
01:16:23.648 --> 01:16:27.478
to cancer epithelial cells. And what we see is

1296
01:16:27.528 --> 01:16:31.448
that starting from an MOI of 10 and up to 100, we

1297
01:16:31.468 --> 01:16:35.248
see significant cell cycle arrest in G0, G1.

1298
01:16:36.408 --> 01:16:40.068
At a MOI of one, the effect

1299
01:16:40.248 --> 01:16:44.188
is pretty minimal. We're not seeing increased proliferation in any

1300
01:16:44.368 --> 01:16:46.988
of these assays.

1301
01:16:48.708 --> 01:16:51.908
When we go back to patient specimens and map what is potentially

1302
01:16:51.928 --> 01:16:55.278
happening, we can use now COSMIC single-cell spatial

1303
01:16:55.308 --> 01:16:58.808
transcriptomics. So again, noting these orthogonal approaches.

1304
01:16:58.868 --> 01:17:02.738
On the left, we have RNA scope. Fusobacterium is yellow, eu

1305
01:17:02.808 --> 01:17:06.368
bacteria is pink. And on the right, we have COSMIC single-cell spatial

1306
01:17:06.408 --> 01:17:08.578
transcriptomics, where we've designed bacterial probes.

1307
01:17:08.608 --> 01:17:12.028
And here I'm just showing you Fusobacterium and eu bacteria.

1308
01:17:12.088 --> 01:17:15.968
So you can see this really nice concordance between the localization of

1309
01:17:16.008 --> 01:17:19.338
bacteria through RNA scope and through COSMIC spatial

1310
01:17:19.408 --> 01:17:23.398
transcriptomics. Again, it's coming from this luminal region infiltrating into

1311
01:17:23.398 --> 01:17:27.188
the tissue. But with COSMIC, we can now identify the different cell types that are

1312
01:17:27.228 --> 01:17:30.288
present in the tumor. And this study was initially with the

1313
01:17:30.508 --> 01:17:33.998
1K gene expression panel, but now there's whole transcriptome

1314
01:17:34.488 --> 01:17:38.388
that has been released this year through COSMIC, so we can get even more

1315
01:17:38.408 --> 01:17:40.728
information on cell interactions.

1316
01:17:41.568 --> 01:17:45.528
You can also see that in the regions that are colonized by bacteria, there's a

1317
01:17:45.548 --> 01:17:48.308
reduction in the diversity of gene transcripts.

1318
01:17:48.368 --> 01:17:50.628
So these cells are still functioning.

1319
01:17:50.688 --> 01:17:54.068
They're producing transcripts, but at a far lower level than

1320
01:17:54.108 --> 01:17:56.388
regions deeper within the tumor tissue.

1321
01:17:58.008 --> 01:18:01.548
And we can carry out niche analysis within these tumors, and we can

1322
01:18:01.828 --> 01:18:05.808
identify the niches where these microbes are localized and start comparing the

1323
01:18:05.828 --> 01:18:09.608
bacterial infected niche to niches that do not harbor bacteria.

1324
01:18:10.098 --> 01:18:13.808
And when we did this, there were several modules that we identified

1325
01:18:13.828 --> 01:18:15.548
associated with the bacterial niche.

1326
01:18:16.048 --> 01:18:19.888
We saw an increase in barrier disruption and adhesion loss, so a reduction

1327
01:18:19.908 --> 01:18:23.628
in Ep-CAM and cadherin. We also saw reduced antigen

1328
01:18:23.708 --> 01:18:27.658
presentation. So remembering that these cells have entered an arrest,

1329
01:18:27.768 --> 01:18:30.928
so metabolism is down, gene expression is down,

1330
01:18:31.528 --> 01:18:35.508
antigen presentation is down. They're essentially in a protected state from our

1331
01:18:35.548 --> 01:18:36.288
immune system.

1332
01:18:37.208 --> 01:18:40.828
And the second module that we saw was an increase in stress and remodeling.

1333
01:18:40.868 --> 01:18:44.158
We saw upregulation of STATs, CXCL8 again, and

1334
01:18:44.188 --> 01:18:45.448
metalloproteases.

1335
01:18:46.388 --> 01:18:49.968
And then this functional consequence is a reduction in the diversity of the

1336
01:18:50.008 --> 01:18:53.668
transcripts per cell, increased cellular spacing between our epithelial

1337
01:18:53.728 --> 01:18:55.588
cells, a reduction in proliferation.

1338
01:18:55.668 --> 01:18:59.268
Again, we're seeing this reduced Ki-67 and overall this G0,

1339
01:18:59.408 --> 01:19:03.372
G1 cell cycle arrest.But the key question was: Is this a

1340
01:19:03.412 --> 01:19:07.252
reversible state? So what's distinguishing this from senescence versus

1341
01:19:07.332 --> 01:19:11.092
quiescence? And we did a range of in vitro and in vivo

1342
01:19:11.132 --> 01:19:14.672
studies to demonstrate that this actually is indeed reversible, that this is a

1343
01:19:14.732 --> 01:19:18.162
quiescence state that Fusobacterium induces.

1344
01:19:18.192 --> 01:19:21.582
Although I'm focusing on Fusobacterium here, we demonstrated this also with

1345
01:19:21.592 --> 01:19:25.492
Bacteroides fragilis, non-enterotoxigenic Bacteroides fragilis, and each

1346
01:19:25.592 --> 01:19:29.412
of the Fusobacterium nucleatum subspecies and sensu lato.

1347
01:19:30.812 --> 01:19:34.652
But the reason why this quiescence state is interesting, especially arrested in

1348
01:19:34.672 --> 01:19:38.182
G0/G1, is that most standard chemotherapies are

1349
01:19:38.212 --> 01:19:40.932
antimetabolites that act in S-phase.

1350
01:19:40.972 --> 01:19:44.912
So if you've got cancer epithelial cells arrested in G0 or G1, how does that

1351
01:19:44.952 --> 01:19:48.812
influence chemotherapy? So we showed that Fusobacterium

1352
01:19:48.992 --> 01:19:52.482
can induce resistance to antimetabolite 5-FU

1353
01:19:53.032 --> 01:19:56.872
based upon induction of this G0/G1 that is reversible upon

1354
01:19:56.892 --> 01:20:00.722
exposure. We also demonstrated this through analysis

1355
01:20:00.832 --> 01:20:04.792
of major pathological response, which was reduced in patients at a

1356
01:20:04.802 --> 01:20:08.312
higher burden of Fusobacterium nucleatum.

1357
01:20:08.372 --> 01:20:11.692
So in the last couple of minutes, I'm going to switch gears slightly because I've

1358
01:20:11.712 --> 01:20:15.172
talked primarily about how these microbes can influence the tumor

1359
01:20:15.212 --> 01:20:18.752
microenvironment, but this interaction is actually bidirectional.

1360
01:20:19.052 --> 01:20:22.172
The tumor microenvironment will also select for the types of

1361
01:20:22.212 --> 01:20:25.182
microbes that can survive and persist within

1362
01:20:25.212 --> 01:20:29.162
them. And this is a study that was carried out by

1363
01:20:29.192 --> 01:20:33.012
Martha Zepeda-Rivera, who was a postdoc between Chris Johnson's lab and my

1364
01:20:33.152 --> 01:20:37.012
lab. And this really centered on trying to understand were there particular

1365
01:20:37.052 --> 01:20:41.012
lineages of Fusobacterium nucleatum that were capable or had an

1366
01:20:41.032 --> 01:20:44.752
increased fitness to get to colorectal tumors and to survive and

1367
01:20:44.792 --> 01:20:48.432
persist within them. And this was a large-scale culturing effort that we had

1368
01:20:48.472 --> 01:20:52.392
carried out, where we assessed Fusobacterium strains

1369
01:20:52.432 --> 01:20:54.132
from patients with colorectal cancers.

1370
01:20:54.552 --> 01:20:58.272
We isolated over 50 unique Fusobacterium

1371
01:20:58.292 --> 01:21:01.292
nucleatum strains from patients and assessed

1372
01:21:01.432 --> 01:21:05.392
their genomics compared to oral

1373
01:21:05.472 --> 01:21:08.871
isolates from patients that did not have cancer.

1374
01:21:08.932 --> 01:21:12.632
And what we saw was that there is two groups, was one group

1375
01:21:12.752 --> 01:21:16.172
called FNA C1, and this was based upon its historical

1376
01:21:16.252 --> 01:21:20.232
16S gene profile, and FNA C2.

1377
01:21:20.972 --> 01:21:24.732
So it looked incredibly similar at the 16S level, but at the genomic level, they

1378
01:21:24.752 --> 01:21:27.352
were essentially different, what were subspecies.

1379
01:21:28.112 --> 01:21:31.932
What was interesting about this is that both were present at

1380
01:21:31.952 --> 01:21:35.612
relatively similar proportions in the oral cavity, but it was this FNA

1381
01:21:35.752 --> 01:21:38.852
C2 or F. animalis sensu

1382
01:21:38.972 --> 01:21:42.092
stricto that dominated the colorectal tumors.

1383
01:21:42.732 --> 01:21:46.092
Phylogenetically, they were each other's closest phylogenetic

1384
01:21:46.132 --> 01:21:49.882
neighbor, so genomically, the most similar within F.

1385
01:21:49.932 --> 01:21:53.832
nucleatum sensu lato. And when we looked at patient cohorts, we

1386
01:21:53.852 --> 01:21:57.772
saw that, yes, F. nucleatum was significantly enriched in tumor tissue

1387
01:21:57.852 --> 01:22:01.672
compared to normal. But when we broke this down, yes, the trend is there

1388
01:22:01.712 --> 01:22:04.752
for all of them, but it was really this clade 2,

1389
01:22:05.692 --> 01:22:09.552
or F. animalis sensu stricto, that was driving this enrichment of

1390
01:22:09.592 --> 01:22:11.732
Fusobacterium in colorectal tumor.

1391
01:22:12.892 --> 01:22:16.232
So this tells us that there is indeed functional selection, that it's not just

1392
01:22:16.352 --> 01:22:19.812
random colonization of tumors by microbes that are

1393
01:22:19.872 --> 01:22:23.542
passing from the oral cavity. And when we looked at

1394
01:22:23.572 --> 01:22:27.512
potential functions comparing this clade 1 to this clade 2, because they

1395
01:22:27.532 --> 01:22:31.332
are each other's closest phylogenetic neighbor, we saw that the clade

1396
01:22:31.652 --> 01:22:35.632
2 had the ability to resist acid in the stomach as a

1397
01:22:35.652 --> 01:22:38.452
potential mechanism for GI tract transit.

1398
01:22:38.492 --> 01:22:42.332
So it had a GAD system that allowed it to

1399
01:22:42.592 --> 01:22:46.252
metabolize glutamate and

1400
01:22:46.592 --> 01:22:50.452
produce GABA and facilitate this enrichment in the colorectal tumor.

1401
01:22:50.492 --> 01:22:54.342
It also had operons for ethanolamine utilization,

1402
01:22:54.472 --> 01:22:58.361
which resembles more enteric pathogens rather than traditional

1403
01:22:58.392 --> 01:22:59.352
oral microbes.

1404
01:23:00.152 --> 01:23:03.252
And I did want to highlight beautiful work from Cindy Sears' group,

1405
01:23:05.512 --> 01:23:07.452
again, with Julia Drews and with Dr.

1406
01:23:07.672 --> 01:23:11.592
Crean, where they demonstrated that there are biofilms, again, across the

1407
01:23:11.632 --> 01:23:12.842
colorectal tumors and that these

1408
01:23:13.912 --> 01:23:14.732
invasive

1409
01:23:15.552 --> 01:23:19.382
biofilms harbor Fusobacterium nucleatum and predominantly this

1410
01:23:19.412 --> 01:23:23.182
clade 2 Fusobacterium nucleatum or the F.

1411
01:23:23.312 --> 01:23:25.332
animalis sensu stricto.

1412
01:23:27.212 --> 01:23:31.072
Again, just highlighting some work from MD Anderson, and this is a study that's

1413
01:23:31.132 --> 01:23:34.262
led by Mike White, who's now currently carrying out a clinical trial looking at

1414
01:23:34.292 --> 01:23:38.232
metronidazole and combining it with standard treatments for patients

1415
01:23:38.312 --> 01:23:42.232
with rectal adenocarcinoma that are undergoing neoadjuvant

1416
01:23:42.792 --> 01:23:46.752
therapy. So assessing whether modulating the microbiome and the

1417
01:23:46.792 --> 01:23:50.472
tumor microbiome, in particular Fusobacterium and co-occurring anaerobes,

1418
01:23:50.812 --> 01:23:53.892
will impact patients' response to standard treatments.

1419
01:23:55.192 --> 01:23:58.432
And with that, just finishing on where our field previously was.

1420
01:23:58.492 --> 01:24:02.412
We were interested in the presence of these microbes correlating, but our

1421
01:24:02.472 --> 01:24:06.312
current understanding is that they are active drivers in modulating

1422
01:24:06.372 --> 01:24:09.562
tumor biology and impacting patient treatment responses,

1423
01:24:10.732 --> 01:24:14.652
impacting heterogeneity, impacting it from a polymicrobial

1424
01:24:14.732 --> 01:24:16.032
ecosystem perspective,

1425
01:24:16.852 --> 01:24:20.512
and also signaling molecules, metabolites that are altering the

1426
01:24:20.552 --> 01:24:24.412
functions of these cells. Where this field is going, I think we can

1427
01:24:24.432 --> 01:24:27.932
apply a range of new emerging technologies to understand this in more

1428
01:24:27.972 --> 01:24:31.432
detail. Things even relating from lineage tracing to

1429
01:24:31.492 --> 01:24:35.032
understand from a clonality perspective how these microbes can

1430
01:24:35.072 --> 01:24:37.432
contribute to metastases or recurrence.

1431
01:24:38.692 --> 01:24:42.152
Building on spatial biology and 3D mapping, we can start to

1432
01:24:42.212 --> 01:24:45.972
understand host microbe interactions in more precise

1433
01:24:46.272 --> 01:24:48.952
and intricate detail than we ever have before.

1434
01:24:48.972 --> 01:24:52.872
And the ultimate goal is to bring this to the clinic and understand how we

1435
01:24:52.912 --> 01:24:56.752
can help patients. So with that, I'll finish thanking patients who

1436
01:24:56.812 --> 01:25:00.562
have contributed to this research, along with my collaborators and my

1437
01:25:00.572 --> 01:25:02.422
funding sources. And thank you for your

1438
01:25:02.452 --> 01:25:10.904
attention.And

